<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Corollary"
         id="Thm_ONBExists"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Existence of an ONB</caption>
   <associate type="Comment">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Existence of an ONB</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Note that this corollary says, in particular, that <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> has an ONB: namely the extension of the empty subset of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> to an ONB of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>In a nonzero subvector space <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math> of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math> every orthonormal subset <math>
               <latex>S</latex>
            </math> of <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math> can be complemented to an orthonormal basis of <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>We know already that 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>
                     <math>
                        <latex>S</latex>
                     </math> is linearly independent</hot>
                  <crossref>
                     <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_OrthogonalmpliesLinearIndependence"/>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Look up this result</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </crossref>
               </subordinate>
			and, hence, 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>can be complemented to a basis of <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math>
                  </hot>
                  <crossref>
                     <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_BasisExists"/>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Look up this result.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </crossref>
               </subordinate>.
			So, if <math>
                  <latex>S=(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_s)</latex>
               </math>, choose an ordered set of linearly independent vectors <math>
                  <latex>T=(\Vect{c}_1,\dots ,\Vect{c}_t)</latex>
               </math> such that</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>\EuScript{A}:=(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_s,\Vect{c}_1,\dots ,\Vect{c}_t)</latex>
         </math.display>
         <para>
            <para.body>is an ordered basis of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. Then apply the Gram-Schmidt process to <math>
                  <latex>\EuScript{A}</latex>
               </math> so as to obtain an ONB <math>
                  <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
               </math> of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>. It only remains to observe that the vectors from <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> remain unchanged as they are already orthonormal, and this completes the proof.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
